en: Vida, y hechos del ingenioso cavallero Don Qvixote de la Mancha
SANCHO PANZA. DON QUIXOTE DE LA MANCHA. AMADIS. ROLANDO. DVLCINEA.

Don Quixote mounted on Rocinante accompanied by Sancho embracing his donkey; at both sides, on pedestals, Roland and Amadis, both as Roman sculptures.On the background, a medallion with Dulcinea's portrait.Simple drawing and quite acceptable engraving.
1 - Based on Savery's I frontis for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (and later editions).
Don Quixote's dinner at the inn

In the foreground, outside the inn, the innkeeper helps don Quixote to drink through his helmet using a cane; also in the scene the party girls (doña Tolosa and doña Molinera).Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but not of great merit.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote fighting with some muleteers during the vigil of his arms / Don Quixote knighted
3.2 Vigil of arms3.3 Fight with muleteer3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper

In the background, don Quixote fighting with the muleteers during the vigil of his arms.In the foreground, the innkeeper knights don Quixote; also doña Tolosa holding don Quixote's sword, doña Molinera fitting his spurs and the boy holding a candle.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Copied after Madrid: Juan S. Martín, 1730 (or later editions), based on Bouttats' illustration for Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73.
Don Quixote helping Andrés / don Quixote attacked by the silk merchants' groom
4.2 Adventure of Andrés4.4 Adventure of the merchants from Toledo

Two scenes in the same illustration (archaic):In the foreground, don Quixote ready to attack Juan Haldudo, who is whipping Andrés.In the background, don Quixote is beaten by one of the silk merchants' grooms.Drawing and engraving are simple and rough.
1 - Copied after Madrid: Juan S. Martín, 1730 (or later editions).

On the left, the priest, the barber and the niece during the scrutiny of don Quixote's library.On the right, don Quixote rests in bed (foreground) while the housekeeper throws his books into the fire (background).Drawing and engraving are simple and rough.
1 - Copied after Madrid: Juan S. Martín, 1730 (or later editions).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Don Quixote fighting with a windmill / Don Quixote fighting with the Basque
8.2 Adventure of the windmills (giants)8.3 Episode with friars of St. Benedict8.4 Adventure with the Basque

Three different scenes (archaic):In the background: don Quixote attacking the windmills and Sancho trying to stop him.In the middle ground, Sancho is beaten by the friars' servants.In the foreground, don Quixote fighting against the Basque; also the carriage with Basque ladies.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but poor.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.2 Grisóstomo´s song14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech14.4 Burial of Grisóstomo

In the foreground, Grisóstomo's corpse surrounded by Ambrosio, Vivaldo (reading Grisóstomo's song), Sancho, don Quixote and other shepherds; a pair of shepherds digging the tomb.In the upper right corner, Marcela's appearance.Drawing and engraving with quite little quality.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote and Sancho attacked by Yangüeses
Don Quixote and Sancho are beaten by Yangüeses.Simple drawing and clumsy engraving.

1 – Poor copy after Diego de Obregón’s illustration (Madrid: Andrés García de la Iglesia, 1674).2 - This illustration was first designed to represent "Don Quixote and Sancho attacked by Cardenio" (p. 146); it has been repeated in both episodes with different wooden blocks.
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Night adventure at the inn with Maritornes

In the foreground, don Quixote lying half-dead on his broken bed.In the background, the fight among Maritornes, Sancho, the muleteer and the innkeeper (holding a candle).Simple drawing and poor engraving.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Sancho Panza's blanketing / Don Quixote fighting with the flock of sheep

In the foreground, at Juan Palomeque's inn, Sancho's blanketing observed by don Quixote from behind the inn wall.In the background, don Quixote attacking a flock of sheep.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote and Sancho encounter a procession of ecclesiastics carrying a dead body.Simple drawing and clumsy engraving.

1 – Poor copy after Diego de Obregón’s illustration (Madrid: Andrés García de la Iglesia, 1674).2 - This illustration was first designed and engraved to represent "Appearance of Merlin's cart" (vol. II, p. 198), but the same image has been repeated in both episodes using the same wooden block.
20.1 Adventure of the fulling mills (batanes)20.4 SP’s mishap (cagada)

During the night, Sancho has to do what no one could do for him (here already raising his breeches).Don Quixote appears covering his nose in reference to the text: "En que ahora más que nunca hueles, y no a ámbar" (20:1).Don Quixote should appear mounted on Rocinante.On the right, Rocinante and Sancho's donkey.In the background, the fulling mills.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote attacks and defeats the barber
21.3 Adventure of the helmet of Mambrino

In the foreground, don Quixote attacking the barber, who gets himself off his mule to avoid the attack; on the ground, the barber basin.In the middle ground, Sancho waving to stop his master.In the background, the same barber running away.Accurate to Cervantes' text, it had begun to rain.Poor drawing and rough engraving.
1 - Copied after Madrid: Juan S. Martín, 1730 (or later editions).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Cardenio attacks don Quixote and Sancho Panza
24.1 Story of Cardenio24.3 Cardenio attacks DQ and SP
In Sierra Morena, don Quixote and Sancho are attacked by mad Cardenio; a goatherd tries to help them.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).2 - Same design (but not same wooden block) has been used for "DQ and SP attacked by Yangüeses" (p. 75).
Jacob Savery / Frederik Bouttats / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Don Quixote's penance in Sierra Morena
25.3 DQ’s letter to Dulcinea25.4 SP’s embassy to Dulcinea;25.5 DQ performs mad acts

In Sierra Morena, before Sancho leaves for El Toboso (village represented in the background?), don Quixote does some somersaults as love penance.Sancho, accurate to Cervantes' text, mounted on Rocinante and with a broom bunch.Don Quixote's arms remain hung on a tree.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 or Bouttats' for Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73.
Dorotea discovered by the priest, the barber and Cardenio
28.1 Priest, barber and Cardenio encounter Dorotea
In Sierra Morena, the barber, the priest and Cardenio discover Dorotea washing her feet beside a stream.Drawing and engraving are quite acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.

Don Quixote tries to punish Sancho hitting him with his lance because the squire has preferred Micomicona's beauty to Dulcinea's.Micomicona (Dorotea) and the priest try to prevent don Quixote from doing it.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Dorotea knelt down before don Fernando
36.2 Resolution of love affairs of Cardenio and Luscinda, Dorotea and Don Fernando

At the inn, Dorotea kneels down before don Fernando and she begs him to allow Luscinda to go with Cardenio.On the floor, Luscinda'stafetán.Also the priest, Sancho, the barber and another figure.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, based on Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote's speech about arms and letters
38.1 DQ speech of arms and letters continues
At the inn, don Quixote makes a speech about arms and letters before Sancho, don Fernando(?) and Dorotea(?).Simple drawing and rough engraving.

1 – Poor copy after Diego de Obregón’s illustration (Madrid: Andrés García de la Iglesia, 1674).2 - This illustration was first designed and engraved to represent "Don Quixote and the ecclesiastic with the Duke and Duchess" (vol. II, p. 176), but it has been used for this chapter too using the same wooden block.
Don Quixote hung and tied to a window
43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand43.3 Four travelers arrive at inn

At dawn (sun), four travelers (servants of don Luis' father) arrive to the inn and Rocinante moves to smell the mares, making don Quixote fall down and remain hung by his hand tied to a window.One of the travelers asks to don Quixote if he is the innkeeper.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote arrested by an officer of the Holy Brotherhood

Two officers of the Holy Brotherhood try to arrest don Quixote at Juan Palomeque's inn; one of them holds a paper with don Quixote's description while the priest reads it.Observing the scene, the innkeeper (?) and two women (his wife and daughter?).Poor drawing and engraving.
Don Quixote enchanted into a cage

Don Quixote is taken back home "enchanted" into a cage on an ox-cart; Sancho appears talking to him through the bars.Also the carter leading the oxen and two officers of the Holy Brotherhood or the barber and the priest on horseback.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote talking with the canon of Toledo

Don Quixote and the canon of Toledo talking about chivalry books; also Sancho observing them.The setting is totally wrong; it should be a landscape, not a library.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote fighting with the goatherd Eugenio / Don Quixote defeated by one penitent
52.1 Fight with the goatherd52.2 Encounter with penitents (disciplinantes)

Two scenes in the same illustration (archaic):In the background, don Quixote fighting with Eugenio; around them, the barber, the priest, Sancho, the canon of Toledo and the officers of the Holy Brotherhood.In the foreground, don Quixote helped by Sancho after having been defeated by one penitent; also the priest talking to the priest of the procession.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Don Quixote as Knight of the Lions with Governor Sancho and Dulcinea enchanted

Don Quixote as Knight of the Lions (a lion behind him); in the background, on a semicircle wall, Sancho as governor and Dulcinea as a peasant girl (enchanted); between them, a medallion with Merlin's portrait.Simple drawing and poor engraving.
1 - Based on Savery's II frontis for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (and later editions).
Don Quixote in bed talking with the priest and the barber
1.1 Priest and barber visit DQ to check if he is cured of his madness
Don Quixote in bed talking to the barber and the priest; also the housekeeper and the niece.Drawing and engraving are acceptable; poor setting.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Don Quixote's encounter with the actors' cart and Sancho's donkey robbery
11.1 Adventure of the cart of actors; “cortes de la muerte”

In the foreground, thebojigangastealing Sancho's donkey.In the middle ground, the cart with actors of Angulo el Malo's company (Devil, Death, Cupid, Angel, Emperor, Queen and Knight or Soldier).On the left, Sancho running to help don Quixote (background), who is falling from Rocinante.Drawing and engraving are acceptable.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote defeats the Knight of the Mirrors
14.2 DQ defeats the knight of the Mirrors
Don Quixote defeating the Knight of the Mirrors (Sansón Carrasco).Drawing and engraving are poor.

1 – Poor copy after Diego de Obregón’s illustration (Madrid: Andrés García de la Iglesia, 1674).2 - This illustration was first designed to represent "DQ defeated by the Knight of the White Moon" (vol. II, p. 363); the same design has been used in both scenes, but with different wooden blocks.
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)

In the foreground, don Quixote ready to fight against a lion, but the animal remains into the cage although the lionkeeper has opened it.In the background, don Diego and Sancho running away.Drawing and engraving are poor.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
22.2 Adventure of the cave of Montesinos

Don Quixote is ready to descend into Montesinos' cave when a flock of birds surprises him.Sancho and the bachelor's cousin hold the rope to which don Quixote is tied.Drawing and engraving are poor, but acceptable.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Don Quixote attacking Maese Pedro's theater and puppets
26.1 Episode of Maese Pedro26.3 DQ attacks and destroys the puppets
Don Quixote raises his sword to attack Maese Pedro's theater; Sancho and other figures observe him.Maese Pedro appears from inside the theater.Drawing and engraving are acceptable, but poor.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Don Quixote discussing with the ecclesiastic

In the Duke´s palace, don Quixote (standing) discusses with an ecclesiastic about chivalry books; the Duchess and Sancho observe them.Simple architectonic setting.The Duke has not been represented, but he should appear.Drawing and engraving are poor.
1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674.
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
35.1 Merlin’s prophecy about Dulcinea and remedy for her enchantment

At night, don Quixote, Sancho, the Duke and the Duchess witness the appearance of Merlin's cart.On the cart, Merlin, Dulcinea and penitents in white robes and holding lighted candles.Strong light and shadow contrasts.Drawing and engraving are poor.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
Jacob Savery / Diego de Obregón (copied after)
Don Quixote and Sancho mounted on Clavileño
41.1 Adventure of Clavileño41.2 DQ and SP fly on Clavileño

In the foreground, don Quixote and Sancho mounted on Clavileño while several servants simulate its flight with a pair of bellows and torches; one of them is lighting its fuse.In the background, the Duke and Duchess.Drawing and engraving are poor.

1 - Copy after Diego de Obregón's illus. for Madrid: A. García de la Iglesia, 1674, copied after Savery´s illustration for Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 (also in Bruselas: Mommarte, 1662; and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672-73).
